IIRC John struggled with the idea of dating Anna because he didn't want to date "One of the enemy" and he ends up running away from her when he loses trust in her after finding out about both her true form and the fate of her father. That's interesting, and gives all of the political nonsense he's been spewing since the beginning a payoff for the reader, in the form of the rejection of Anna, who until this point we thought was going to be the girl of his dreams. The difference between the deer story and this one is that the irreverence has value in generating conflict, and is taken into account when the characters make decisions. In the deer story, at best, it's a crappy in-joke that only serves to lower the quality of your work, and at worst, it actively alienates readers.
I don't have an issue with irreverence as long as there's a reason it's there. Crossing the line is warranted if you're doing it to make a well-articulated point in an argument, or if you use it for character development, conflict, or world-building within fiction.
I've been on 4chan for years, so I know how irreverent it can get, and I don't want the writer to make the mistake of pandering to that irreverence without making sure it's in his story for a good reason.
